                                    &#160;</div></ulink></entry></row></tbody></tgroup></table><para> Before introducing Tamboti's Basic Input forms, we need to talk a little about the structure of bibliographical entries in general. </para><para> Bibliographical entries basically divide into three blocks of information, that is, information
            concerning </para><ul><li>the publication itself, </li><li>the container that the publication occurs in, and</li><li>the location of the publication inside its container.</li></ul><para> Monographs that belong in a monograph series, articles that belong in a periodical and contributions to edited volumes that belong in an anthology all follow
            this pattern. Monographs that occur on their own, monographs that are not part of any series, only have the first block
            of information, but that presents no complications: the last two blocks are simply left empty. 
            The same applies to descriptions of series and periodicals as such.</para><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" border="1" width="75%" class="center"><col width="25%"/><col width="25%"/><col width="25%"/><col width="25%"/><tbody><tr><td/><td align="center" valign="middle">Publication</td><td align="center" valign="middle">Container</td><td align="center" valign="middle">Location in Container</td></tr><tr><td>Monographs</td><td align="center" valign="middle">X</td><td align="center" valign="middle"/><td align="center" valign="middle"/></tr><tr><td>Monographs in series</td><td align="center" valign="middle">X</td><td align="center" valign="middle">X</td><td align="center" valign="middle">X</td></tr><tr><td>Periodicals</td><td align="center" valign="middle">X</td><td align="center" valign="middle"/><td align="center" valign="middle"/></tr><tr><td>Articles in periodicals</td><td align="center" valign="middle">X</td><td align="center" valign="middle">X</td><td align="center" valign="middle">X</td></tr><tr><td>Edited volumes</td><td align="center" valign="middle">X</td><td align="center" valign="middle"/><td align="center" valign="middle"/></tr><tr><td>Edited volumes in series</td><td align="center" valign="middle">X</td><td align="center" valign="middle">X</td><td align="center" valign="middle">X</td></tr><tr><td>Contributions to edited volumes</td><td align="center" valign="middle">X</td><td align="center" valign="middle">X</td><td align="center" valign="middle">X</td></tr></tbody></table><para> The Basic Input Forms accommodate these types of bibliographical entries. This means that it can deal with the larger part of standard
            bibliographical entries. More types will be added.</para></chapter></book>